<paragraph blockId="12.[160,1156,1349,1721]" lastBlockId="13.[160,1156,142,271]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="324" pageId="12" pageNumber="323">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,225,1349,1375]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="323">Male.</emphasis>
General morphology similar to that of female except for posterior region being more ventrally curved. Genital system diorchic, testes opposed, sperm cells spindleshaped, 5.0–6.0 μm long. In addition to adcloacal pair, situated at 7.0–9.0 µm from cloacal aperture, there are three to four irregularly spaced ventromedian supplements, located outside the range of spicules; first ventromedian supplement located 25–29 μm from adcloacal pair. Spicules typically dorylaimoid, curved ventrad, relatively slender, 5.8–7.3 times as long as wide and 1.3–1.6 times as long as cloacal body diameter, dorsal contour regularly convex, ventral contour bearing a moderately developed hump and hollow, curvature 130–136°, head occupying 12–16% of total spicules’ length, median pieces 12.5–16.5 times as long as wide, occupying 37–50% of the spicules’ maximum width, reaching the spicules’ tip, posterior end 2.0–2.5 μm wide. Lateral guiding pieces distinct, rod-like, 4.7–6.0 times as long as wide or about one-fourth of the spicules’ length. Prerectum 5.0–6.6 and rectum 1.3–1.6 cloacal body diameter long. Tail elongated to long filiform with rounded tip, tapering gradually, its distal part bent dorsally, 5.1–5.8 times cloacal body diameter long, with a pair of caudal pores on each side.
</paragraph>
